    "text": "Below is a complete textual description of the DFD\u2019s elements and their connections, with each element labeled using STRIDE-per-element categories.\n\nElements\n- User (Browser) (External Entity): Human end user operating a web browser. Provides prompts/inputs and receives the application\u2019s outputs.\n- Streamlit UI (Process): The web front end running inside the app container. Renders the interface, accepts user input, and displays the agent\u2019s final answer.\n- LangChain ReAct Agent (Process): Core orchestration logic. Receives the user request from the UI, optionally calls tools, composes prompts to the LLM provider, aggregates observations, and returns the final answer to the UI.\n- Tool Dispatcher (tools.py & utils.py) (Process): Executes tool calls made by the agent. In this diagram it primarily mediates database access and returns observations/results to the agent.\n- SQLite DB (transactions.db) (Data Store): Local file-backed database. Stores transactional data queried by tools; returns result rows to the Tool Dispatcher.\n- Config files (.env, yaml, toml) (Data Store): Local configuration and secrets store. Contains agent configuration, API keys/credentials, DB path, and tool settings.\n- LLM Provider (OpenAI/HF/Ollama) (External Entity): Remote model service reached over the internet. Receives model requests and returns LLM responses.\n\nData flows\n- User input (Data Flow): User (Browser) -> Streamlit UI. User types a prompt or selects UI controls.\n- Output (Data Flow): Streamlit UI -> User (Browser). UI renders the final answer and any interim messages to the user.\n- submit (Data Flow): Streamlit UI -> LangChain ReAct Agent. The UI forwards the user\u2019s request to the agent.\n- final answer (Data Flow): LangChain ReAct Agent -> Streamlit UI. Agent returns the completed response for display.\n- tool call (Data Flow): LangChain ReAct Agent -> Tool Dispatcher. Agent requests execution of a tool (e.g., a DB read).\n- Observation (Data Flow): Tool Dispatcher -> LangChain ReAct Agent. Tool results sent back to the agent as observations.\n- SQL query (Data Flow): Tool Dispatcher -> SQLite DB (transactions.db). Dispatcher issues SQL queries.\n- rows (Data Flow): SQLite DB (transactions.db) -> Tool Dispatcher. Query results returned.\n- Agent config & API key (Data Flow): Config files (.env, yaml, toml) -> LangChain ReAct Agent. Agent reads model/provider configuration and credentials.\n- Tool/DB config (Data Flow): Config files (.env, yaml, toml) -> Tool Dispatcher. Tools read DB path, tool parameters, and other settings.\n- API key / LLM request (Data Flow): LangChain ReAct Agent -> LLM Provider (OpenAI/HF/Ollama). Agent sends model requests, authenticated with an API key or local model selection.\n- LLM response (Data Flow): LLM Provider (OpenAI/HF/Ollama) -> LangChain ReAct Agent. Model output returned to the agent.\n\nTrust boundaries (not elements; do not classify)\n- AppContainer Boundary: Encloses Streamlit UI, LangChain ReAct Agent, Tool Dispatcher, SQLite DB, and Config files. Data crossing this boundary includes:\n  - User input and Output between the User\u2019s browser (outside) and Streamlit UI (inside).\n  - API key / LLM request and LLM response between the Agent (inside) and the LLM Provider (outside).\n  This boundary represents the host/container where the app executes; intra-boundary communications are considered internal.\n- Internet Boundary: Encloses the LLM Provider. Communications crossing into/out of this boundary are the API key / LLM request and the LLM response, typically over HTTPS/public networks.\n\nEnd-to-end flow summary\n1) User enters a prompt in the Streamlit UI.\n2) UI submits the prompt to the LangChain ReAct Agent.\n3) Agent may read configuration (including API key) and send a request to the LLM Provider; receives the LLM response.\n4) Agent may issue tool calls to the Tool Dispatcher, which queries the SQLite DB and returns rows as observations.\n5) Agent synthesizes a final answer and returns it to the Streamlit UI.\n6) UI presents the output back to the User.",
